Top 10 Mountain Ranges in the World

  • Author:
    spliffic09
  • Updated:
    Jul 11, 2024 8:49 PM EDT

The Most Famous Mountain Ranges on Earth

Mountain ranges exist on every continent. Here are some of Earth's highest, longest, and most famous ranges. In this top 10 list, we are going to start with the ranges with the highest peaks (including four sub-ranges of the Himalayan system), move on to some of the longest ranges, and end with a few mellow old ranges on quiet continental margins.

Why Are There High Mountain Ranges in Asia?

The earth’s surface is constantly moving a few centimeters a year. This means that continents are riding the drifting geologic plates. Where the plates collide, under or next to a continent, the crust thickens into mountains. Continental and ocean-floor rocks are crumpled and thrust over each other, sometimes along with slices of the mantle from under the ocean floor. These parts of the mantle are often pierced with volcanoes that erupt masses of molten material squeezed out of the deeply buried crust.

As shown in the map below, all of south-central Eurasia is festooned with mountain ranges. A succession of smaller landmasses slamming into the southern edge of Eurasia have raised up many mountain ranges: the Himalayan complex, the Tien Shan, the Caucasus, and the Alps, among many others.

1. The Himalayan Mountain System

In south-central Asia, the ongoing collision between the Indian plate and the Eurasian plate has raised up the world's most mountainous area, the Himalayan orogenic belt. The area began rising in the last 50 million years and continues to rise at about 5 mm a year as the collision continues.

Since both plates were covered with lightweight continental crust, which tends to float on top of the heavier mantle layer, the crust from both plates were crumpled together. In addition, the ocean floor between the two moving continents was swept up and stacked between them. The top of Mount Everest itself is sedimentary rock from the ocean's bottom.

The Himalayan region contains the world's greatest accumulation of ice outside the Arctic and Antarctic. The world’s hundred tallest peaks are nearly all in the Himalayas. There is Karakoram, Pamirs, and the Hindu Kush. (A few exceptions are also in southern Asia, in China's Hengduan Mountains and Kunlun Shan.) The world's 14 8000-meter peaks are all in the Himalayas proper or the Karakoram.

The Himalaya Range

  • Elevation: 8,848.86 m (29,031.7 ft)
  • Range: 2,400 km (1,500 mi)
  • Peak: Mount Everest
  • Location: Bhutan, China, India, Nepal, and Pakistan

The Himalaya Range (meaning "home of snow"), stretching from Pakistan to Bhutan, separates the Indian subcontinent from the Tibetan Plateau. The world's highest peak, Mount Everest, at 29,031 feet, is in the Himalayas, as are scores of massive, beautiful, and dangerous peaks. It is a popular travel destination, but many climbers have given their lives to ascend the peak. The snowfields on the range supply great rivers like the Ganges, the Indus, and the Brahmaputra.

Karakoram Mountains

  • Elevation: 8,611 m (28,251 ft)
  • Range: 500 km (310 mi)
  • Peak: K2
  • Location: Afghanistan, China, India, Pakistan, and Tajikistan

The Karakoram (meaning "black gravel") mountains of Pakistan mark the western end of the greater Himalayan mountain chain and contain the greatest concentration of high peaks on earth.

The Karakoram is a mountain desert: a vast region of barren rock and ice, of gravel-covered glaciers where jeep roads cut through valley systems to remote villages still many days' walk from the high mountains.

Hindu Kush

  • Elevation: 7,708 m (25,289 ft)
  • Range: 800 km (500 mi)
  • Peak: Tirich Mir
  • Location: Afghanistan, Tajikistan, and Pakistan

The Hindu Kush, part of the Himalayan complex, is a group of ranges in Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Tajikistan. The name is said to mean "Killer of Hindu." The Khyber Pass crossing it, connecting Afghanistan with India and Pakistan, has long been of great military importance, including during the 21st-century invasion of Afghanistan by the U.S.

Pamir Range

  • Elevation: 7,649 m (25,095 ft)
  • Range: 900 km (559 mi)
  • Peak: Kongur Tagh
  • Location: Tajikistan, Kyrgyzstan, Afghanistan, China, and Pakistan

The Pamir Range, which runs through Pakistan, Afghanistan, Tajikistan, Kyrgyzstan, and China, trends more north-south than the other Himalayan ranges. The ancient Silk Road, the long and dangerous land route between China and Europe, crossed it. Its highest peak is the 25,095-foot Kongur Tagh.

2. Tian Shan

  • Elevation: 7,439 m (24,406 ft)
  • Range: 2,900 km (1,800 mi)
  • Peak: Jengish Chokusu
  • Location: China, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Uzbekistan, and Tajikistan

The Tian Shan (also known as Tenri Tagh or Tengir-Too) continues eastward from the Hindu Kush into China. It is separated from the Himalayan ranges and Tibet to the south by the huge Taklimakan Desert in the Tarim Basin. The Tian Shan marks the northern boundary of another microcontinent that rammed into the southern edge of Asia before India did. Compression in the area is lifting the range up.

3. Andes Mountains

  • Elevation: 6,961 m (22,838 ft)
  • Range: 8,900 km (5,500 mi)
  • Peak: Aconcagua
  • Location: Argentina, Bolivia, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Venezuela

The world's longest mountain chain, and the highest outside Asia, is the Andes. It runs 5,500 miles from Colombia to the southern tip of South America. Unlike the Asian mountain ranges, which resulted from collisions between continents, the Andes are a result of plates bearing ocean crust colliding with the continent of South America.

Since the Cretaceous period (about 65 million years ago, the time of the dinosaurs), the ocean crust has been sliding below the west coast of South America, sinking, melting, and causing volcanoes and uplift. The Andes are part of the "Ring of Fire" surrounding the Pacific, marked by volcanoes, earthquake zones, and deep ocean trenches. The glaciers and snowfields of the Andes supply water to the arid coast of central South America as well as to the Amazon Basin.

The Andean peak Aconcagua, like Everest, is one of the Seven Summits; that is, it is the highest peak on its continent.

4. Alaska Range

  • Elevation: 6,190 m (20,310 ft)
  • Range: 900 km (600 mi)
  • Peak: Denali
  • Location: United States

The Alaska Range is a long, narrow, curved range that traverses Alaska from the Aleutian Peninsula to the Yukon Territory. In its bend in Central Alaska, it has the highest mountain in North America. The 20,310-foot Denali (formerly known as Mt. McKinley) is one of the Seven Summits (the highest mountain in North America), and it's one of the world's tallest mountains from base to top.

The geology here is complex; like much of the western margin of North America, Alaska is made of strips of continents that came from somewhere else. In Alaska, the faults that bound the strips have been bent so that Denali, made of lightweight granite, popped up at the corner under pressure from a subduction zone far to the south in the Gulf of Alaska. It dominates the surrounding peaks and is visible from great distances, seeming to float above its surroundings.

5. Caucasus Range

  • Elevation: 5,642 m (18,510 ft)
  • Range: 1,200 km (750 mi)
  • Peak: Mount Elbrus
  • Location: Russia, Georgia, Azerbaijan, and Armenia

The Caucasus is another Eurasian range that resulted from a subcontinent, the Iranian Plate, running into the Eurasian land mass. The range is between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea. Volcanism has surged in the area in the last few million years, creating volcanic peaks like Mt. Elbrus (18,510 feet), the highest mountain in Europe and one of the Seven Summits.

6. The Alps

  • Elevation: 4,808.73 m (15,776.7 ft)
  • Range: 1,200 km (750 mi)
  • Peak: Mont Blanc
  • Location: Austria, France, Germany, Italy, Liechtenstein, Monaco, Slovenia, and Switzerland

The Alps formed by an approaching continent (Africa) smashing into Eurasia, along with great sheets of the sea floor, beginning about 50 million years ago. Stretching around Northern Italy from Monaco through France, Switzerland, and Austria to Slovenia, this range contains many huge flat-lying folds called nappes, in which rocks from the vanished ocean Tethys are stacked on top of European rocks and, in turn, covered by rocks from Africa.

The European pastimes of geology and mountain climbing originated in large part in the Alps in the 1700s and 1800s.

7. Transantarctic Mountains

  • Elevation: 4,528 m (14,856 ft)
  • Range: 3,500 km (2,200 mi)
  • Peak: Mount Kirkpatrick
  • Location: Antarctica

The Transantarctic Mountains deserve mention, in part because they are a long mountain range. At 2,200 miles, they run from McMurdo Sound, the base of 19th-century Antarctic exploration, in a gentle S-shape across the continent to the Weddell Sea. They are an old range at 500 million years. They are largely covered with snow and ice; only their tallest peaks poke out of the ice as nunataks.

Robert Scott's expedition geologized there, finding sedimentary rocks, including coal, full of plant fossils. The range is also home to the Dry Valleys, which are sheltered glacial valleys containing the few patches of bare soil on the continent. Although Antarctica has one of the Seven Summits (Mount Vinson, 16,050 ft), it is not in the Transantarctic Mountains. Mount Vinson is found in the younger Ellsworth Mountains.

8. Rocky Mountains

  • Elevation: 4401.2 m (14,440 ft)
  • Range: 4,828 km (3,000 mi)
  • Peak: Mount Elbert
  • Location: Canada and United States

The Rocky Mountains are another lengthy range. It runs 3,000 miles from New Mexico to western Canada. Mt. Elbert in Colorado is its highest peak. The Rockies are located between the Great Plains on the east (from which they rise abruptly for most of their length) and a series of broad basins and plateaus on the west.

For a long time, plate tectonics had no good explanation for the Rockies' existence. They are not obviously a plate margin; for much of the range's history, the plate boundary has been far to the west, along the western edge of the continent. One explanation (for example, in Keith Heyer Meldahl's book This Rough-Hewn Land) is that much of the Farallon plate formerly to the west has been dragged underneath western North America, and its slowly melting remnants are supporting the Rockies and the Colorado Plateau.

9. Great Dividing Range

  • Elevation: 2,228 m (7,310 ft)
  • Range: 3,500 km (2,200 mi)
  • Peak: Mount Kosciuszko
  • Location: Australia

The Great Dividing Range is a long and old mountain range (from the Carboniferous period 300 million years ago) with complex geology. It runs from Queensland to New South Wales. Its Snowy Mountains gets winter snow, has alpine scenery, and contains the highest point in Australia, Mt. Kosciuszko at 7,310 feet. As the highest point on a continent, it makes the list of the Seven Summits, if you do not include New Guinea's Punczak Jaya (16,024) as the highest point in the region of Oceania.

10. Ural Mountains

  • Elevation: 1,894 m (6,214 ft)
  • Range: 2,500 km (1,550 mi)
  • Peak: Mount Narodnaya
  • Location: Russia and Kazakhstan

The Ural Mountains extend for 1,550 miles from the hot Kazakh steppes to the frozen coast of the Arctic Ocean. The Urals are old mountains (about 250 to 300 million years) that were formed at the boundary between two plates when Kazakhstania collided with Laurussia. Their highest peak is Mount Narodnaya at 6,214 feet.

Mountain Ranges of All Kinds

These are some of the world's tallest and longest ranges. But even the lesser ranges provide beauty, adventure, solitude, wildlife habitat, and water. In closing, we are going to visit a couple of less spectacular ranges that nevertheless are beautiful.

Serra do Mar

  • Elevation: 2,255 m (7,398 ft)
  • Range: 1,500 km (932 m)
  • Peak: Pico da Caledônia
  • Location: Brazil

I'd like to include a couple old, low ranges from Gondwanaland (the southern hemisphere) that don't record any recent great tectonic collisions but do provide scenery, waterfalls, and water supplies. Brazil's coastal mountains run from Espiritu Santo to Santa Catarina, along the Atlantic Coast. They are more of a discontinuous escarpment than a mountain range.

Eastern Ghats

  • Elevation: 1,680 m (5,510 ft)
  • Range: 1,700 km (1,100 mi)
  • Peak: Sitamma Kanda
  • Location: India

The Eastern and Western Ghats—escarpments at the edge of a stable continent—form the edges of the Deccan Plateau in southern India. The Eastern Ghats extend about 1,100 miles, with an average elevation of about 2,000 ft (600 m). The Western Ghats run some 800 miles along the southwestern and western coast, with average elevations from 3,000 ft (900 m) to 5,000 ft (1,500 m). Because they receive heavy rainfall during the monsoon season, the Western Ghats are peninsular India's main watershed.
